cblind

Elisa Thouverai

2022-09-21

#Required packages
require(cblindplot)

Introduction

cblind package enables colour blind people to easily visualize maps made with various palettes in a “colour blind friendly” format by changing the palette based on the colour blind deficiency selected. In this vignette we will demonstrate how to use the package.

Input data preparation

The image used as an exaple is colored with rainbow palette and represents the NDVI values of Falzarego in June 2022. To correctly upload the image in R, the function cblind.prep() that convert the image in a “SpatRaster” object (terra package) can be used:

im <- cblind.prep("rainbow_ndvi.png")

Using the arguments crop_manual or select_class, the user can crop the image manually or with the use of unsupervised classification in case of an irregular shape, so that the background is excluded.

The crop_manual argument enable the user to manually select the area of the image he wants to crop:

im_cr <- cblind.prep("rainbow_ndvi.png", crop_manual = T)

Instead, using the select_class argument the map area is selected by the user after an unsupervised classification where the background is separetad from the image:

im_cl <- cblind.prep("rainbow_ndvi.png", select_class = T)

Plot construction

The image uploaded with cblind_prep() function can be now elaborated to change the palette. Here, the image not modified:

cblind.plot(im, cvd = "protanopia") 
cblind.plot(im, cvd = "deuteranopia")
cblind.plot(im, cvd = "tritanopia")

As for the manually cropped image:

cblind.plot(im_cr, cvd = "protanopia") 
cblind.plot(im_cr, cvd = "deuteranopia")
cblind.plot(im_cr, cvd = "tritanopia")

And last, the classified image:

cblind.plot(im_cl, cvd = "protanopia") 
cblind.plot(im_cl, cvd = "deuteranopia")
cblind.plot(im_cl, cvd = "tritanopia")
